om/api/questions/13916/relationships/activeRevision"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"packs":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/packs","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/relationships/packs"}},"revisions":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/revisions","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/relationships/revisions"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13916"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/content","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/relationships/content"}},"specialtyTags":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/specialtyTags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/relationships/specialtyTags"}},"primaryTags":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/primaryTags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/relationships/primaryTags"}},"contributionTypes":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/contributionTypes","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/relationships/contributionTypes"}},"contributors":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/contributors","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/relationships/contributors"}},"contribution":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/contribution","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/relationships/contribution"}},"myContribution":{"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/myContribution","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/relationships/myContribution"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"100608"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/activeRevision","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/relationships/activeRevision"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1927"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/tags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/relationships/tags"}},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13089"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13091"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14233"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46332"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46338"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/contributions","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6535/relationships/contributions"}}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"118796","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/118796"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of excessive daytime sleepiness. She reports falling asleep during meetings, while watching television, and occasionally while eating. During these episodes, she recalls vivid dreams and hearing voices as she falls asleep. Her medical history includes a viral illness one year ago, from which she has fully recovered. She takes no regular medications. She lives with her partner, who has not observed any snoring outside of periods when she has been unwell with a common cold. She has not had previous known apnoeas. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her body mass index is 24 kg/m\u00b2 and her neck circumference is 35 cm. Her Epworth Sleepiness Scale score is 18 out of 24.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Obstructive sleep apnoea","Chronic fatigue syndrome","Idiopathic hypersomnia","Hypothyroidism","Narcolepsy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003Enarcolepsy\u003C/strong\u003E. The patient presents with classic symptoms of excessive daytime sleepiness, including falling asleep in inappropriate situations (during meetings, watching TV, and while eating). Her very high Epworth Sleepiness Scale score of 18 indicates severe daytime sleepiness. Key features that distinguish narcolepsy from other causes of excessive daytime sleepiness include vivid dreams during naps, hypnagogic hallucinations, and sleep paralysis. These additional symptoms are characteristic of narcolepsy and help differentiate it from idiopathic hypersomnia. It is important to note that while the Epworth Sleepiness Scale is a useful tool for assessing daytime sleepiness, it is not specific to any particular sleep disorder and does not directly measure the risk of obstructive sleep apnoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObstructive sleep apnoea\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely in this case. This can be assessed using the STOP-BANG questionnaire (Snoring, Tiredness, Observed apnoea, high blood Pressure, BMI, Age, Neck circumference, Gender), which evaluates the risk of obstructive sleep apnoea. In this case, the patient\u0027s STOP-BANG score is 1 (for tiredness), which indicates a low risk of obstructive sleep apnoea. She does not meet other criteria: no snoring, no observed apnoeas, no high blood pressure, BMI \u0026lt; 35 kg/m\u00b2, age \u0026lt; 50, neck circumference \u0026lt; 40 cm, and female gender. This low STOP-BANG score, combined with the absence of typical obstructive sleep apnoea symptoms, makes obstructive sleep apnoea quite unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdiopathic hypersomnia\u003C/strong\u003E is a possibility, as it also presents with excessive daytime sleepiness. However, narcolepsy is more likely given the presence of vivid dreams during naps suggestive of REM sleep, hypnagogic hallucinations, and sleep paralysis, which are not typically seen in idiopathic hypersomnia. Furthermore, the severity of the symptoms and specific mention of falling asleep while eating is more characteristic of narcolepsy. Ultimately, a multiple sleep latency test (MLST) will be required to confirm the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic fatigue syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with fatigue rather than sleepiness and patients usually do not fall asleep involuntarily, as described in this case. The Epworth Sleepiness Scale score would likely be lower in chronic fatigue syndrome. While the patient\u0027s history of a viral illness one year ago might raise consideration for chronic fatigue syndrome, the pattern of symptoms is more consistent with narcolepsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E can cause fatigue and sleepiness, but it typically does not cause such severe daytime sleepiness with involuntary sleep attacks. Additionally, hypothyroidism often presents with other symptoms such as weight gain, cold intolerance, and constipation, which are not mentioned in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETo confirm the diagnosis of narcolepsy, further testing would be required, including a polysomnogram followed by a multiple sleep latency test. These tests can help differentiate narcolepsy from other causes of excessive daytime sleepiness.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Narcolepsy is characterised by excessive daytime sleepiness, often with a high Epworth Sleepiness Scale score, but may have low risk for obstructive sleep apnoea if other risk factors are absent.","A high Epworth Sleepiness Scale score (\u003E10) indicates significant daytime sleepiness and warrants further investigation.","The Epworth Sleepiness Scale measures daytime sleepiness, while risk factors for obstructive sleep apnoea are assessed separately using tools like the STOP-BANG questionnaire."],"references":["Pagel JF. Excessive daytime sleepiness. Am Fam Physician. 2009 Mar 1;79(5):391-6. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19275068/","Akintomide GS, Rickards H. Narcolepsy: a review. Neuropsychiatr Dis Treat. 2011;7:507-18. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3173034/","Chervin, RD. \u201cApproach to the Patient with Excessive Daytime Sleepine.\u201d UpToDate, 2025, www.uptodate.com/contents/approach-to-the-patient-with-excessive-daytime-sleepiness?search=hypersomnia%20idiopathic\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=2~15\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=2. Accessed 8 Oct. 2025."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"100608"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/118796/itemRevision","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/118796/relationships/itemRevision"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13916"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/118796/question","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/118796/relationships/question"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/118796/stemMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/118796/relationships/stemMedia"}},"explanationMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/118796/explanationMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/118796/relationships/explanationMedia"}}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"100608","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/100608"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-10-08T18:44:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-10-08T18:45:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6535"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/100608/item","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/100608/relationships/item"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"118796"},"li